  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "According to the pointing ויּענני, the poet appears to base his present petition, which from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 120:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " onwards is the substance of the whole Psalm, upon the fact of a previous answering of his prayers. For the petition in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 120:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " manifestly arises out of his deplorable situation, which is described in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 120:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Nevertheless there are also other instances in which ויענני might have been expected, where the pointing is ויּענני (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 3:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jonah 2:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), so that consequently ויּענני may, without any prejudice to the pointing, be taken as a believing expression of the result (cf. the future of the consequence in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 9:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") of the present cry for help. צרתה, according to the original signification, is a form of the definition of a state or condition, as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 3:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 44:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 63:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jonah 2:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hosea 8:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and בּצּרתה לּי  equals  בּצּר־לּי, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 18:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", is based upon the customary expression צר לּי. In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 120:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " follows the petition which the poet sends up to Jahve in the certainty of being answered. רמיּה beside לשׁון, although there is no masc. רמי (cf. however the Aramaic רמּי, רמּאי), is taken as an adjective after the form טריּה, עניּה, which it is also perhaps in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Micah 6:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The parallelism would make לשׁון natural, like לשׁון מרמה in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 52:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; the pointing, which nevertheless disregarded this, will therefore rest upon tradition. The apostrophe in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 120:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is addressed to the crafty tongue. לשׁון is certainly feminine as a rule; but whilst the tongue as such is feminine, the לשׁון רמיה of the address, as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 52:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
